I currently have that setting on 'disabled' which allows students to show up as anon to classmates but not to instructors. To echo what <@UEPUV52GL> said, with the correct intention, anon posting is definitely one of the main features I previously found useful as a student due to fear of "asking stupid questions".

i’d caution to not completely turn off anon posting, cause then some students are afraid to ask questions (feel stupid, afraid of backlash, usual question fears). We tried that before too, and it greatly reduced the number of questions asked. best compromise we found was to allow anon posting, but instructors could still see who was posting
Thx Ian!!!
<@UF83RJTHD> can we turn off anonymous posting of any kind?
^ <@UF83RJTHD> <@U1D40QFD4>, not sure which of you is leading this

I’ve used this at previous teaching jobs to huge success with students (albiet this was years and years ago). One thing to keep in mind though: as great as a tool as it is, anonymous posting can lead to some pretty toxic conversations if things aren’t moderated. Be wary of that.

Also there used to be an admin setting that allowed for students to post anonymously to everyone (students + staff) or just to students (i.e. if a student posts anonymously, other students will see “anon”, while staff will see the name. I found the later greatly reduced toxic convos since students still knew that staff knew who was saying stuff

Hello TAs!  I've been working with some students who have been getting a lot of TA support (YEAH).  I asked them if when a TA unblocked them did they understand what the TA did (ie searched google, read the errors, looked in documentation, ....) or if it *"Felt Like Magic"* .

They all said there were times when it *"Felt Like Magic"*.  So - I asked them that the next time that happens to ask the TA to do it again / slower so that they understand and it no longer seems like magic.  They were nervous to do this since they are so thankful for your help, but agreed to try

Letting you all know so if you get the request to "Do it again so it doesn't feel like magic" you'll know.   When we unblock students, the most important part is that they learn from the process and get better at unblocking themselves.

Thanks for all the support you give students!

Example: it’s about 11:30 AM PST – if I plan on working until 1PM, I don’t think Tsheets will allow you to state 1PM as a Time Out time. You have to wait until you’ve either completed your timeblock for today and then retroactively commit the time, or you have to click the checkbox for *Currently Working* until 1PM.

I had a similar issue a while back – it’s not an issue with Tsheets. If you’re working currently, you have to click the _Status_ symbol to be *Currently Working*. You cannot create a timeslot with a _Time Out_ time that’s in the future. You can only retroactively track timeslots.
